<div class="legal-document">
  <div class="legal-header">
    <h1>Privacy Policy</h1>
    <p class="legal-jurisdiction">Australia (AU) — Privacy Act 1988 (Cth) and Australian Privacy Principles</p>
    <p class="legal-version">Version <%= legal_version %> | Effective: 1 March 2026</p>
  </div>

  <div class="legal-body">

    <h2>1. INTRODUCTION</h2>
    <p><strong>1.1</strong> FutureProof Financial Pty Ltd, ACN [TBD] ("FutureProof", "we", "us", "our") is committed to protecting your personal information in accordance with the <%= details[:privacy_act] %>.</p>
    <p><strong>1.2</strong> This Privacy Policy explains how we collect, hold, use, disclose, and protect your personal information when you use the FutureProof Platform, apply for or hold an Equity Preservation Mortgage ("EPM"), or otherwise interact with us.</p>
    <p><strong>1.3</strong> We are bound by the 13 Australian Privacy Principles ("APPs") set out in Schedule 1 to the Privacy Act 1988 (Cth), as well as the credit reporting provisions in Part IIIA of the Privacy Act.</p>
    <p><strong>1.4</strong> By providing your personal information to us or using the Platform, you consent to the collection, use, and disclosure of your personal information in accordance with this Privacy Policy.</p>
    <p><strong>1.5</strong> We may update this Privacy Policy from time to time. The current version will always be available on our website.</p>

    <h2>2. WHAT PERSONAL INFORMATION WE COLLECT (APP 3)</h2>
    <p><strong>2.1</strong> We collect the following categories of personal information as reasonably necessary for our functions and activities:</p>

    <h3>2.2 Identity Information</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Full legal name, including any former names;</li>
      <li>(b) Date of birth;</li>
      <li>(c) Gender;</li>
      <li>(d) Government-issued identification numbers (driver's licence, passport, Medicare card);</li>
      <li>(e) Photograph or image for identity verification;</li>
      <li>(f) Signature.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2.3 Contact Information</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Residential address and postal address;</li>
      <li>(b) Email address;</li>
      <li>(c) Telephone numbers (mobile, home, work);</li>
      <li>(d) Emergency contact details.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2.4 Financial Information</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Income details (employment income, pension, investment income, government benefits);</li>
      <li>(b) Assets and liabilities;</li>
      <li>(c) Bank account and payment details;</li>
      <li>(d) Existing loan and mortgage details;</li>
      <li>(e) Superannuation details (where relevant to suitability assessment);</li>
      <li>(f) Centrelink Customer Reference Number and benefit details (where relevant);</li>
      <li>(g) Credit history and credit scores.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2.5 Property Information</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Property address and legal description;</li>
      <li>(b) Title details and encumbrances;</li>
      <li>(c) Valuation reports and property data;</li>
      <li>(d) Insurance details (building, contents, strata);</li>
      <li>(e) Council rates and land tax information;</li>
      <li>(f) Strata or body corporate information (where applicable).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2.6 Employment Information</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Current and previous occupation;</li>
      <li>(b) Employer name and contact details;</li>
      <li>(c) Employment status (employed, self-employed, retired);</li>
      <li>(d) Length of employment.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2.7 Tax Information</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Tax File Number (TFN);</li>
      <li>(b) Tax residency status;</li>
      <li>(c) Australian Business Number (ABN), if applicable.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>We are authorised to collect your TFN under the Income Tax Assessment Act 1936 (Cth). Providing your TFN is not compulsory, but if you choose not to provide it, withholding tax may be deducted from investment income at the highest marginal rate.</p>

    <h3>2.8 Health Information</h3>
    <p>We may collect limited health information where it is directly relevant to assessing the suitability of an EPM for you (for example, life expectancy considerations for term selection). We only collect health information with your explicit consent and handle it with the highest level of care in accordance with the APPs.</p>

    <h3>2.9 Technical Information</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Device information (browser type, operating system, device identifiers);</li>
      <li>(b) IP address and approximate geographic location;</li>
      <li>(c) Usage data (pages visited, features used, session duration);</li>
      <li>(d) Cookie and tracking data (see Section 13);</li>
      <li>(e) Log files and error reports.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>3. HOW WE COLLECT INFORMATION (APP 3.5)</h2>
    <p><strong>3.1</strong> We collect personal information from the following sources:</p>

    <h3>3.2 Directly from You</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) When you register for an account on the Platform;</li>
      <li>(b) When you complete an EPM application form;</li>
      <li>(c) When you communicate with us (email, phone, chat, in person);</li>
      <li>(d) When you use the Platform and its features;</li>
      <li>(e) When you provide documents to support your application.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3.3 From Third Parties</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) <strong>Credit Reporting Bodies:</strong> Equifax, Experian, and illion (credit reports, credit scores, credit history);</li>
      <li>(b) <strong>Property Valuers:</strong> Independent valuation firms engaged to assess your property;</li>
      <li>(c) <strong>Government Agencies:</strong> Services Australia (Centrelink), Australian Taxation Office (ATO), state revenue offices, land titles offices;</li>
      <li>(d) <strong>Identity Verification Providers:</strong> Electronic identity verification services for KYC/AML compliance;</li>
      <li>(e) <strong>Your Authorised Representatives:</strong> Financial advisors, legal representatives, or other persons you have authorised to act on your behalf;</li>
      <li>(f) <strong>Lenders and Insurers:</strong> In the course of processing your EPM application;</li>
      <li>(g) <strong>Publicly Available Sources:</strong> Electoral rolls, public registers, court records (for identity verification and fraud prevention).</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>3.4</strong> Where it is reasonable and practicable, we collect personal information directly from you. We will only collect information from third parties where you have consented, where we are authorised by law, or where it is unreasonable or impracticable to collect it directly from you.</p>

    <h2>4. WHY WE COLLECT INFORMATION (APP 6)</h2>
    <p><strong>4.1</strong> We collect, hold, use, and disclose your personal information for the following purposes:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) <strong>Application Processing:</strong> To assess and process your EPM application, including verifying your identity, assessing your eligibility, and conducting property valuations;</li>
      <li>(b) <strong>Credit Assessment:</strong> To assess your creditworthiness and conduct responsible lending assessments as required by the National Consumer Credit Protection Act 2009 (Cth);</li>
      <li>(c) <strong>Responsible Lending:</strong> To make inquiries about your financial situation, requirements, and objectives, and to assess whether the EPM is not unsuitable for you;</li>
      <li>(d) <strong>KYC/AML Compliance:</strong> To verify your identity and comply with our obligations under the <%= details[:aml_act] %>, including customer due diligence and ongoing monitoring;</li>
      <li>(e) <strong>Loan Servicing:</strong> To manage your EPM account, process Monthly Income payments, provide statements, and administer the Investment Portfolio;</li>
      <li>(f) <strong>Fraud Prevention:</strong> To detect, prevent, and investigate fraud, money laundering, and other financial crimes;</li>
      <li>(g) <strong>Risk Management:</strong> To manage credit risk, investment risk, and operational risk associated with EPM products;</li>
      <li>(h) <strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> To comply with our obligations under the Corporations Act 2001 (Cth), the NCCP Act, the Privacy Act, the AML/CTF Act, taxation laws, and other applicable legislation;</li>
      <li>(i) <strong>Customer Support:</strong> To respond to your enquiries, complaints, and requests;</li>
      <li>(j) <strong>Product Improvement:</strong> To improve our products, services, and the Platform (using de-identified or aggregated data where possible);</li>
      <li>(k) <strong>Marketing:</strong> To send you information about our products and services (with your consent, which you may withdraw at any time).</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>5. USE AND DISCLOSURE (APP 6)</h2>
    <p><strong>5.1</strong> We may disclose your personal information to the following categories of recipients:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) <strong>Lenders:</strong> Wholesale funders and lending institutions that provide the mortgage finance for your EPM;</li>
      <li>(b) <strong>Investment Managers:</strong> Appointed investment managers responsible for managing the Investment Portfolio;</li>
      <li>(c) <strong>Property Valuers:</strong> Independent valuers engaged to assess the market value of your property;</li>
      <li>(d) <strong>KYC/AML Providers:</strong> Identity verification and screening service providers;</li>
      <li>(e) <strong>Insurers:</strong> Lenders mortgage insurers and other insurance providers relevant to the EPM;</li>
      <li>(f) <strong>Credit Reporting Bodies:</strong> Equifax, Experian, and illion (see Section 7);</li>
      <li>(g) <strong>ASIC:</strong> The <%= details[:regulator] %>, as required by law or in response to regulatory enquiries;</li>
      <li>(h) <strong>ATO:</strong> The Australian Taxation Office, for tax reporting purposes;</li>
      <li>(i) <strong>Services Australia:</strong> Where relevant to your Centrelink entitlements and with your consent;</li>
      <li>(j) <strong>AFCA:</strong> The Australian Financial Complaints Authority, in connection with any complaint or dispute;</li>
      <li>(k) <strong>Professional Advisors:</strong> Our legal, accounting, and audit advisors, under professional confidentiality obligations;</li>
      <li>(l) <strong>Technology Providers:</strong> Cloud hosting, data storage, and IT service providers (under contractual data protection obligations);</li>
      <li>(m) <strong>Law Enforcement:</strong> Police and other law enforcement agencies, where required by law or to prevent or detect crime.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>5.2</strong> We will only disclose your personal information for the purposes described in this policy, or where otherwise permitted or required by law.</p>

    <h2>6. NO SALE OF PERSONAL INFORMATION</h2>
    <p><strong>6.1</strong> We do not sell, rent, or trade your personal information to any third party for marketing or commercial purposes.</p>
    <p><strong>6.2</strong> We do not disclose your personal information for direct marketing by third parties without your explicit consent.</p>
    <p><strong>6.3</strong> If we send you direct marketing communications about our own products and services, you may opt out at any time by using the unsubscribe link in our emails or by contacting our Privacy Officer.</p>

    <h2>7. CREDIT REPORTING (PART IIIA OF PRIVACY ACT)</h2>
    <p><strong>7.1</strong> As a credit provider, we participate in the credit reporting system regulated by Part IIIA of the Privacy Act 1988 (Cth) and the Privacy (Credit Reporting) Code 2014 (Version 2.2).</p>
    <p><strong>7.2 Credit Information We May Disclose:</strong> We may disclose the following credit information about you to credit reporting bodies:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Identity information (name, date of birth, address);</li>
      <li>(b) The type and amount of credit sought or provided;</li>
      <li>(c) That you have applied for credit and the amount;</li>
      <li>(d) That we are a credit provider to you;</li>
      <li>(e) Repayment history information;</li>
      <li>(f) Default information (if applicable);</li>
      <li>(g) That credit has been paid or otherwise discharged.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>7.3 Credit Reporting Bodies:</strong> We may exchange credit information with the following credit reporting bodies:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) <strong>Equifax:</strong> equifax.com.au | Phone: 138 332</li>
      <li>(b) <strong>Experian:</strong> experian.com.au | Phone: 1300 783 684</li>
      <li>(c) <strong>illion:</strong> illion.com.au | Phone: 1300 734 806</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>7.4 Access to Your Credit Report:</strong> You have the right to request a free copy of your credit report from any of the above credit reporting bodies once every three (3) months, or within 90 days of a credit application being declined.</p>
    <p><strong>7.5 Correcting Credit Information:</strong> If you believe any credit information held about you is inaccurate, you may request a correction from us or from the relevant credit reporting body. We will respond to correction requests within 30 days.</p>
    <p><strong>7.6 Credit Reporting Body Policies:</strong> Each credit reporting body has its own privacy policy governing how it handles your credit information. We encourage you to review their policies.</p>

    <h2>8. DATA SECURITY (APP 11)</h2>
    <p><strong>8.1</strong> We take the security of your personal information seriously and have implemented the following measures to protect it from misuse, interference, loss, unauthorised access, modification, and disclosure:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) <strong>Encryption:</strong> AES-256 encryption for data at rest and TLS 1.3 encryption for data in transit;</li>
      <li>(b) <strong>Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA):</strong> Required for account access, administrative functions, and high-value transactions;</li>
      <li>(c) <strong>Role-Based Access Controls (RBAC):</strong> Access to personal information is restricted to authorised personnel on a need-to-know basis;</li>
      <li>(d) <strong>Penetration Testing:</strong> Regular independent security assessments and penetration testing of our systems;</li>
      <li>(e) <strong>Security Monitoring:</strong> Continuous monitoring for suspicious activity and security threats;</li>
      <li>(f) <strong>Staff Training:</strong> Regular privacy and security training for all staff who handle personal information;</li>
      <li>(g) <strong>Incident Response:</strong> Documented incident response procedures for data security incidents;</li>
      <li>(h) <strong>Physical Security:</strong> Secure facilities with controlled access for any physical records;</li>
      <li>(i) <strong>Vendor Assessment:</strong> Due diligence on all third-party service providers to ensure adequate data protection standards.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>8.2</strong> While we take reasonable steps to protect your personal information, no method of electronic storage or transmission is 100% secure. We cannot guarantee absolute security of your data.</p>

    <h2>9. DATA RETENTION AND DESTRUCTION (APP 11.2)</h2>
    <p><strong>9.1</strong> We retain your personal information only for as long as necessary to fulfil the purposes for which it was collected, or as required by law. Our retention periods are:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) <strong>Active EPM Accounts:</strong> For the duration of the EPM plus seven (7) years after the loan is discharged;</li>
      <li>(b) <strong>Closed or Discharged Accounts:</strong> Seven (7) years from the date of closure or discharge;</li>
      <li>(c) <strong>Unsuccessful Applications:</strong> Two (2) years from the date of the decision, unless you request earlier deletion;</li>
      <li>(d) <strong>AML/CTF Records:</strong> Seven (7) years from the date the account is closed, as required by the AML/CTF Act;</li>
      <li>(e) <strong>Credit Information:</strong> As required by Part IIIA of the Privacy Act and the Privacy (Credit Reporting) Code;</li>
      <li>(f) <strong>Tax Records:</strong> Five (5) years from the date the record was prepared or the transaction completed, as required by the Income Tax Assessment Act;</li>
      <li>(g) <strong>Marketing Preferences:</strong> Until you withdraw your consent.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>9.2</strong> When personal information is no longer required and there is no legal obligation to retain it, we will take reasonable steps to destroy or de-identify the information.</p>
    <p><strong>9.3</strong> Destruction methods include secure deletion for electronic records and secure shredding for physical records.</p>

    <h2>10. CROSS-BORDER DISCLOSURE (APP 8)</h2>
    <p><strong>10.1</strong> In the course of providing our services, your personal information may be disclosed to recipients located outside Australia, including in the following countries:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) <strong>United States:</strong> Cloud infrastructure providers (e.g., AWS, Google Cloud), investment data providers;</li>
      <li>(b) <strong>United Kingdom:</strong> FutureProof Financial group entities and service providers;</li>
      <li>(c) <strong>New Zealand:</strong> FutureProof Financial group entities;</li>
      <li>(d) <strong>Other Countries:</strong> Where our third-party service providers maintain operations.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>10.2</strong> Before disclosing personal information to an overseas recipient, we take reasonable steps to ensure that the recipient does not breach the APPs, including by:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Entering into contractual arrangements requiring compliance with data protection standards substantially similar to the APPs;</li>
      <li>(b) Conducting due diligence on the recipient's data protection practices;</li>
      <li>(c) Ensuring that the recipient is subject to a law or binding scheme that is substantially similar to the APPs (where applicable).</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>10.3</strong> In accordance with APP 8.1, we remain accountable for any acts or practices of overseas recipients that would breach the APPs.</p>

    <h2>11. YOUR RIGHTS (APP 12, APP 13)</h2>
    <p><strong>11.1 Right of Access (APP 12):</strong> You have the right to request access to the personal information we hold about you. To make an access request, contact our Privacy Officer using the details in Section 16. We will respond to your request within 30 days.</p>
    <p><strong>11.2</strong> We may refuse access in limited circumstances permitted by the Privacy Act, including where:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Providing access would pose a serious threat to life, health, or safety;</li>
      <li>(b) Providing access would unreasonably impact the privacy of other individuals;</li>
      <li>(c) The request is frivolous or vexatious;</li>
      <li>(d) Providing access would reveal our commercially sensitive decision-making processes (though we will still provide the factual information on which the decision was based);</li>
      <li>(e) Access is denied or restricted by law.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>11.3</strong> If we refuse access, we will provide you with written reasons for the refusal and the mechanisms available to you to complain about the refusal.</p>
    <p><strong>11.4 Right of Correction (APP 13):</strong> You have the right to request correction of personal information we hold about you that is inaccurate, out of date, incomplete, irrelevant, or misleading. We will respond to correction requests within 30 days.</p>
    <p><strong>11.5</strong> If we refuse to correct your personal information, we will provide you with written reasons and advise you of your right to request that a statement be associated with the information noting that you consider it inaccurate.</p>
    <p><strong>11.6 Right to Complain:</strong> If you believe we have breached the APPs or mishandled your personal information, you have the right to lodge a complaint with us (see Section 16) and, if not resolved, with the Office of the Australian Information Commissioner (OAIC).</p>

    <h2>12. NOTIFIABLE DATA BREACHES (PART IIIC)</h2>
    <p><strong>12.1</strong> We comply with the Notifiable Data Breaches (NDB) scheme under Part IIIC of the Privacy Act 1988 (Cth).</p>
    <p><strong>12.2</strong> If we become aware of an eligible data breach (or have reasonable grounds to believe one has occurred), we will:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Conduct a reasonable and expeditious assessment to determine whether the breach is likely to result in serious harm to any affected individuals;</li>
      <li>(b) If the breach is assessed as an eligible data breach, notify the OAIC and all affected individuals as soon as practicable;</li>
      <li>(c) Include in the notification: a description of the breach, the kinds of information involved, recommendations about the steps individuals should take in response, and our contact details;</li>
      <li>(d) Take reasonable steps to contain the breach and mitigate any harm.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>12.3</strong> We maintain a data breach response plan and conduct regular testing to ensure we can respond effectively to data security incidents.</p>
    <p><strong>12.4</strong> If you become aware of any suspected data breach or unauthorised access to your account, please contact us immediately using the details in Section 16.</p>

    <h2>13. COOKIES AND TRACKING</h2>
    <p><strong>13.1</strong> The Platform uses cookies and similar tracking technologies for the following purposes:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) <strong>Essential Cookies:</strong> Required for Platform functionality, authentication, and security. These cannot be disabled;</li>
      <li>(b) <strong>Analytics Cookies:</strong> Used to understand how visitors interact with the Platform, helping us improve our services. These collect anonymised usage data;</li>
      <li>(c) <strong>Preference Cookies:</strong> Used to remember your settings and preferences for a more personalised experience.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>13.2</strong> We do not use cookies for behavioural advertising or to track you across third-party websites.</p>
    <p><strong>13.3</strong> You can manage your cookie preferences through your browser settings. Disabling essential cookies may affect Platform functionality.</p>
    <p><strong>13.4</strong> For more information about how cookies work, visit allaboutcookies.org.</p>

    <h2>14. CHILDREN'S PRIVACY</h2>
    <p><strong>14.1</strong> The Platform and our services are not intended for use by persons under 18 years of age. We do not knowingly collect personal information from children.</p>
    <p><strong>14.2</strong> If we become aware that we have collected personal information from a person under 18, we will take reasonable steps to delete that information as soon as practicable.</p>
    <p><strong>14.3</strong> If you believe we have inadvertently collected information from a minor, please contact our Privacy Officer immediately.</p>

    <h2>15. CHANGES TO THIS POLICY</h2>
    <p><strong>15.1</strong> We may update this Privacy Policy from time to time to reflect changes in our practices, legal requirements, or business operations.</p>
    <p><strong>15.2</strong> For material changes, we will notify you via email or through a prominent notice on the Platform at least 30 days before the changes take effect.</p>
    <p><strong>15.3</strong> The date of the most recent revision will be indicated at the top of this policy. We encourage you to review this policy periodically.</p>
    <p><strong>15.4</strong> Your continued use of the Platform after the effective date of any changes constitutes acceptance of the revised Privacy Policy.</p>

